super() keyword is use for calling the constructor parent and it should in the line inside of constructor

Example

public class Superb extends SuperBase {

    public(String message){
    super(message); // as you can see we declare the super keyword at the first line inside of constructor

    others..
    }
}

and we can use it like this:

Superb child = new Superb("hello from child class");
// the new keyword is invoked which itself invoked the parent constructor first and passes the string data.



Accessing parent class viriables.


public class SuperBase {

    String message = "Hi from super class"

    public SuperBase(String message){
    this.message = message;
    }
  }

in the child class

public class Superb extends SuperBase {

    String message = "child class"

    public void getParentMessage(){
    System.out.println(super.message)
    }
}

we can access the parent class by using the super with dot if its inside the method.



































